description: Emesis zela.  This species is found in the US only in a very restricted band along the Mogollon Rim in Arizona, although it is listed as common in appropriate habitat there -- namely, riparian sycamore woods,  which is exactly where I found it.  Got a good look thru binocs -- hindwing above bright orange with concentric dark banding, forewing above with dark shading along the central part of the median line.  Unfortunately it didn't let me get a shot -- only one I got was a zoom macro with it perched far above our heads in a tree.

description: Photo shows one individual seen near the Maze Loop Trail parking area. The plant is yucca buckwheat, Erigonum plumatella. What's unusual about this observation is that only three individual butterflies were seen during a four-hour field excursion doing scouting for a planned fall butterfly count. All three butterflies were Desert Mexican Metalmarks. In the last several years, this amount of effort would have produced between 15-20 species and 100-300 individuals. Lack of monsoon rains in the park this year appear to have seriously depressed  fall butterfly populations.

description:
I *think* these images show Rounded Metalmark rather than Fatal Metalmark which is the species usually encountered in central Texas. #ncowey has had this species here recently, and comparting my own images from south Texas in previous years, I believe that is what these are, based on the rounded bulge of the metallic postmedian band on the forewing as well as the paler interior of the wings. I tried to illustrate this rounded bulge in image 4. @aredoubles @nlblock any thoughts?

@dhend9 @ericisley and I went to Bastrop County today and met up with @ncowey at McKinney Roughs Nature Park where Nick works. 
http://www.lcra.org/parks/developed-parks/Pages/mckinney-roughs-nature-park.aspx
The park is owned and managed by the L.C.R.A. (Lower Colorado River Authority). Nick was very gracious and gave us a good tour of the park and we found a bunch of things to iNat as well as a new odonate or two for the park.

Bastrop Co., Texas

The problem is that in the fall it flies together with Apodemia mejicanus deserti, also found at this location.

description: Seems like A. hepburni and A. murphyi are both really close, but murphyi has a terminal band of white dots on the top side of the hindwing and and a broad, unbroken white band on the bottom side of the hindwing, neither of which I'm seeing here.

I use this name with some hesitation because it seems like it was previously considered a subspecies of M. cephise, but on http://www.butterfliesofamerica.com and on iNat, individuals white white margins on the forewing seem to be called Melanis acroleuca now (see https://www.inaturalist.org/observations/1961516#identification-3803855). However, I can find no evidence of a publication that actually elevates it from subspecies to full species. Can anyone provide that citation? I suspect it might be the "J. White & A. White, 1989" paper that serves as the authority for Melanis acroleuca huasteca at http://www.butterfliesofamerica.com/L/t/Melanis_acroleuca_a.htm, but I think that might actually refer to Adolpho White López and another "J" White López and I'm getting tripped up by Spanish patrilineal surname transmission (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_naming_customs#Generational_transmission). Maybe the reference I seek is La fauna de mariposas de México parte I. Papilionoidea (Lepidoptera : Rhopalocera)

description: Found in numbers nectaring on Citharexylum brachyanthum (Berlandier's Fiddlewood).  National Butterfly Center.

National Butterfly Center.  Found in great numbers along the trunk and main branches of this Guamuchil tree (Pithecellobium dulce).  Today probably saw 50 or so adult Red-bordered Pixie butterflies at this location, about ten caterpillars, 30 pupae, and hundreds of empty chrysalises.  The larvae congregate in great numbers to pupate along the trunks.
